Analysis on Adelaide CBD Air Quality Data

Background

The Environment Protection Authority (EPA) monitors South Australian airsheds in order to assess the air quality and provide information that can be used to guide management decisions. This data set contains validated particle pollution data for the Adelaide CBD region. This site was commissioned in April 2014.

Set-up libraries:

library("tidyverse")
library("lubridate", "dplyr", "forcats")

First we should load all the datasets from data.sa.au We got 36 data sets representing 36 months from April 2014 up to March 2017. We have placed them all in a folder and in the code below, we will merge them into one dataset.

# Writing the function "multmerge" to merge multiple datasets. It takes the path of the input files (mypath) and ouput file (output_file) as arguments.
multmerge <- function(mypath,output_file) {
  filenames = list.files(path = mypath, full.names = TRUE)
  DF <-  read.csv(filenames[1])
  for (f in filenames[-1]) DF <- rbind(DF, read.csv(f))   
  write.csv(DF, output_file, row.names=FALSE, quote=FALSE)
}
multmerge(mypath = "./ADL07p", output_file = "particle.csv")
particle <- read.csv("particle.csv")

Data Exploration

We should organize the dates to its proper format and rename the columns for easy access. We also separate a column for each the components of time like year, month, days of the week and hour of the day.

summarise(particle, avg_pm10 = mean(pm10, na.rm =TRUE), avg_pm2.5 = mean(pm2.5, na.rm = TRUE))

Now, lets see what hours have the highest particulate matter(PM). To simplify our analysis, we choose to focus first on PM10 variable.

ggplot(particle, mapping = aes(x=hour, y=pm10)) +
  geom_point(position = "jitter", na.rm = TRUE, alpha = 1/10)+
  geom_smooth(na.rm = TRUE)+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(0:23))

This plot does not show clearly the fluctuation of PM per hour. Perhaps, if we cluster our data per month and take the averages of particular hour, we can see a pattern.

The plot above suggests that there are most PM10 in the air on average during the day from 1pm to around 2pm then gradually lessens until when the air is cleanest at around 3am to 4am.

Some months have pretty high average hourly rates so we can suspect that the season and time of the year has and effect on it. Lets try color-coding the plot by month and see if there is a pattern.

We can observe in the plot above that the months of November to January have higher PM rating than the other months. We can theorise that there is a relationship of season being dry or wet on the air quality. To prove this theory, we have to group our months by season:

fct_reorder(particle$season, season_order)

Error: length(f) == length(x) is not TRUE

Our hypothesis is confirmed: there is seasonal pattern affecting air quality in Adelaide CBD. Although we have to dig further to find out what factors in the season that affect the air quality.

This time, we are now interested in translating our findings into numbers.

We also like to investigate how our data in Adelaide CBD compare to acceptable healthy measurements.
